      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>Domain Authority (DA)</strong> is a proprietary Moz score, 1 to 100, that predicts how likely a site is to rank in Google’s organic results. It blends more than 40 signals—dominated by the number and quality of referring domains—into a single logarithmic number. DA is <strong>not a Google ranking factor</strong>. It is a directional benchmark for link prospecting, competitive analysis, and progress tracking.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Metric</div>
            <div class="tms-value"><span class="http-code-chip">DA 1–100</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Off-Page SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Correlation to rankings</div>
            <div class="tms-value">~0.2</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">DA is the single most misused number in SEO. Used as a compass, it accelerates link prospecting and competitive analysis. Used as a KPI, it drives teams to chase vanity metrics that Google itself does not care about.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is Domain Authority?</h2>
        <p>Domain Authority is a machine-learning score built by Moz that estimates a domain’s overall ranking potential. It sits on a 1-to-100 logarithmic scale, meaning moving from DA 20 to 30 is far easier than moving from DA 70 to 80. Moz recalculates DA on a periodic cadence as it recrawls the web.</p>
        <p>Because the scale is logarithmic, small numeric gains at the top compound. A DA 80 site typically has orders of magnitude more link equity than a DA 40 site, not twice as much.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Google’s stance</div>
          <p>Google has publicly stated that DA is <strong>not a ranking factor</strong>. Its internal system, PageRank, is a related but separate concept. DA remains useful only as a proxy—the backlinks it measures are the actual signals Google acts on.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why Domain Authority matters</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Link prospecting.</strong> Filter guest-post opportunities and outreach targets by DA to avoid wasting time on low-quality sites.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive benchmarking.</strong> Compare your DA to the top-ranking sites for your target keywords. If they are DA 70 and you are DA 15, target long-tail queries first.</li>
          <li><strong>Client reporting.</strong> DA growth is easy to explain in a monthly report. It shows progress even when rankings are still catching up.</li>
          <li><strong>Toxic-link detection.</strong> Sudden DA drops usually signal an influx of spam links that need to be disavowed.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How Domain Authority is calculated</h2>
        <p>Moz’s machine-learning model analyses 40+ inputs. The heaviest weights sit on the backlink graph:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Total unique referring domains</li>
          <li>Quality (DA) of those referring domains</li>
          <li>Anchor-text diversity and relevance</li>
          <li>Spam signals across the link profile</li>
          <li>Historical trend of link acquisition</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The output is normalized to a 1–100 logarithmic scale so that scores remain comparable as the web grows.</p>

        <h2 id="types">DA ranges by business type</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Site type</th><th>Typical DA</th><th>Signal</th><th>What to focus on</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr><td><strong>Brand-new site</strong></td><td>1–10</td><td>Fresh domain</td><td>Foundational links, content velocity</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Local business</strong></td><td>20–35</td><td>Competitive locally</td><td>Local citations, community links</td></tr>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>National SMB</strong></td>
                <td>35–55</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">Strong for most queries</td>
                <td>Digital PR, resource pages</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Enterprise / publisher</strong></td><td>60–80</td><td>Category leader</td><td>Original research, syndicated links</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Major brand</strong></td><td>80–100</td><td>Household name</td><td>Reputation management</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real Domain Authority examples</h2>
        <p>Three patterns from real client work show how DA moves in practice.</p>

        <h3>1. Local law firm: DA 1 to 18 in six months</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Month 0: fresh domain</span><br>
          Starting DA: <span class="uf-status">1</span> &middot; Referring domains: 0<br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-comment"># Program: weekly blog + local citations + one news feature</span><br>
          Month 6 DA: <span class="uf-status">18</span> &middot; Referring domains: 47
        </div>

        <h3>2. Guest-post evaluation</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Two opportunities to compare</span><br>
          Site A: DA <span class="uf-status">54</span>, clean referral base <span class="uf-new">→ accept</span><br>
          Site B: DA <span class="uf-status">12</span>, spammy neighbourhood <span class="uf-old">→ skip</span>
        </div>

        <h3>3. Agency reporting</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># HVAC client, 30 articles/month + digital PR</span><br>
          Month 0 DA: <span class="uf-old">14</span><span class="uf-arrow">→</span>Month 8 DA: <span class="uf-new">29</span><br>
          Organic sessions: <span class="uf-new">+312%</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Domain Authority vs Domain Rating</h2>
        <p>Both DA and DR predict ranking strength from backlinks. The difference is what each metric weights and how it updates.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use DA (Moz) when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You already work in Moz Pro or Link Explorer</li>
              <li>You want a metric that includes spam-score signals</li>
              <li>You are evaluating overall domain quality, not raw link volume</li>
              <li>Your client reports historically show DA</li>
              <li>You are prospecting for guest posts with editorial vetting</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use DR (Ahrefs) when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You work in Ahrefs as your primary SEO stack</li>
              <li>You care about raw referring-domain graph strength</li>
              <li>You need near-real-time updates as new links appear</li>
              <li>You are running large-scale link audits</li>
              <li>Your competitors are also benchmarked in Ahrefs</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 best practices for growing Domain Authority</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Prioritise diverse referring domains.</strong> 10 links from 10 different sites outperform 100 links from a single domain.</li>
          <li><strong>Earn, don’t buy.</strong> Purchased links inflate DA short-term but trigger Moz spam flags and Google manual actions.</li>
          <li><strong>Build gradually.</strong> Suspicious velocity spikes get penalised by both Moz’s spam score and Google’s link-graph filters.</li>
          <li><strong>Create link-worthy assets.</strong> Original research, industry data, and definitive guides earn passive links for years.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit toxic links quarterly.</strong> Disavow spammy referring domains before they drag DA down.</li>
          <li><strong>Fix technical issues first.</strong> A crawlable, indexable site is a prerequisite—no link equity flows to broken pages.</li>
          <li><strong>Benchmark competitors, not universal targets.</strong> DA 40 is elite in one niche and mediocre in another. Compare against SERP peers only.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — chasing DA instead of rankings</div>
          <p>Teams spend months lifting DA from 25 to 35 without moving a single keyword. DA is a proxy for authority, not a substitute for content relevance, technical health, or search intent match. Rankings—not DA—drive traffic and revenue.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common Domain Authority mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Treating DA as a Google ranking factor.</strong> It is not. Google’s John Mueller has confirmed this multiple times.</li>
          <li><strong>Prioritising DA over topical relevance.</strong> A DA 30 link from a niche-fit site beats a DA 70 link from an unrelated blog.</li>
          <li><strong>Buying bulk links to inflate DA.</strong> Moz spam signals catch it fast; Google follows shortly after.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring page-level authority.</strong> A high-DA site does not guarantee any specific page ranks—Page Authority is the page-level counterpart.</li>
          <li><strong>Comparing DA across niches.</strong> DA 30 is competitive in local plumbing and irrelevant in SaaS.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is a good Domain Authority score?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Context matters more than the raw number. Local businesses are competitive at DA 20–30. National brands typically hold DA 50+. Compare against your direct SERP competitors rather than chasing a universal target.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does Google use Domain Authority?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. DA is a third-party Moz metric. Google has repeatedly confirmed it does not use DA as a ranking signal, though the backlinks DA measures are ranking signals in their own right.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How long does it take to improve Domain Authority?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Expect 3–6 months of consistent link building for meaningful movement. Growing from DA 1 to DA 20 is achievable in a year with steady effort; DA 40 to DA 50 can take 2+ years because the scale is logarithmic.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Is a higher Domain Authority always better?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. A high-DA site with irrelevant content will underperform a lower-DA site with strong on-page SEO and topical fit. DA should complement content strategy, not replace it.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
